{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17621938","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17621938"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:00:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:00:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16780"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16780"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9471"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75084"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9471"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16780"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60591"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5386"},{"type":"tags","id":"5392"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22393"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23077"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75084","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75084"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPublic health systems use various methods to monitor disease occurrence in populations. One important approach involves healthcare workers regularly submitting reports about specific conditions of interest, regardless of whether cases have been detected.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes active surveillance in public health?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Retrospective analysis of hospital records","Periodic population health surveys","Voluntary reporting of cases by clinicians","Regular systematic collection of data with immediate follow-up","Collection of mortality statistics"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegular systematic collection of data with immediate follow-up\u003C/strong\u003E is the defining characteristic of active surveillance. This approach involves healthcare workers proactively searching for and reporting cases of specific conditions, even when no cases are found. The data is analysed in real-time to enable rapid public health response.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVoluntary reporting of cases by clinicians\u003C/strong\u003E describes passive surveillance, where healthcare providers only report cases when they encounter them.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERetrospective analysis of hospital records\u003C/strong\u003E involves examining historical data rather than current cases.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECollection of mortality statistics\u003C/strong\u003E represents routine vital statistics monitoring rather than active surveillance.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeriodic population health surveys\u003C/strong\u003E provide point-in-time data rather than the continuous monitoring required for active surveillance.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EActive surveillance is particularly valuable for monitoring serious infectious diseases, emerging health threats, and conditions requiring immediate public health intervention. It provides more timely and complete data than passive surveillance systems.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Active surveillance involves systematic collection, analysis, and interpretation of health data for immediate public health action.","Active surveillance requires healthcare workers to regularly report specific conditions, even when no cases are detected.","Active surveillance is particularly important for serious infectious diseases requiring rapid response."],"references":["Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60591"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16780"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60591"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T21:23:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T21:24:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9471"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75084"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"5326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5326"},"attributes